verline {x}}}"></span> is also a solution, so, when speaking of the number =
of solutions of a linear congruence we are referring to the number of diffe=
rent congruence classes that contain solutions.=20
</p><p>If <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">d</span=
> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greatest_common_divisor" =
title=3D"Greatest common divisor">greatest common divisor</a> of <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span> and <span class=3D=
"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> then the linear congru=
ence <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>ax</i> =E2=89=A1 <i>b</i> (mod <i>m</i>)</s=
pan> has solutions if and only if <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fon=
t-style:italic;">d</span> divides <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fon=
t-style:italic;">b</span>. If <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-st=
yle:italic;">d</span> divides <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-st=
yle:italic;">b</span>, then there are exactly <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" =
style=3D"font-style:italic;">d</span> solutions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_multiplica=
tive_inverse#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A modular multiplicative inverse of an integer <span class=3D"texhtm=
l mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span> with respect to the modulus <=
span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> is a solu=
tion of the linear congruence
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
