idue_system_modulo_m" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Complete residue syste=
m modulo m"><b>complete system of residues modulo <span class=3D"texhtml mv=
ar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span></b></a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_multipli=
cative_inverse#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Division_algorithm_for_integers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Di=
vision algorithm for integers">division algorithm</a> shows that the set of=
 integers, <span class=3D"texhtml">{0, 1, 2, ..., <i>m</i> =E2=88=92 1} </s=
pan> form a complete system of residues modulo <span class=3D"texhtml mvar"=
 style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span>, known as the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Least_residue_system_modulo_m" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Least residue system modulo m"><b>least residue system modulo <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span></b></a>. In wor=
king with arithmetic problems it is sometimes more convenient to work with =
a complete system of residues and use the language of congruences while at =
other times the point of view of the congruence classes of the ring <span c=
