n class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span>.
</p><p>In a general <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring_with_a_un=
it" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ring with a unit">ring with unity</a> no=
t every element has a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiplicati=
ve_inverse" title=3D"Multiplicative inverse">multiplicative inverse</a> and=
 those that do are called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_(ri=
ng_theory)" title=3D"Unit (ring theory)"><b>units</b></a>. As the product o=
f two units is a unit, the units of a ring form a <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Group_(mathematics)" title=3D"Group (mathematics)">group</a=
>, the <b>group of units of the ring</b> and often denoted by <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>R</i><sup>=C3=97</sup></span> if <span class=3D"texhtml mva=
r" style=3D"font-style:italic;">R</span> is the name of the ring. The group=
 of units of the ring of integers modulo <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> is called the <b>multiplicative group of i=
ntegers modulo <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m<=
/span></b>, and it is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isomorphism"=
 title=3D"Isomorphism">isomorphic</a> to a reduced residue system. In parti=
cular, it has <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Order_(group_theory)=
" title=3D"Order (group theory)">order</a> (size), <span class=3D"mwe-math-=
element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-=
