<p>A modular multiplicative inverse of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span> modulo <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> can be found by using the extended Euclide=
an algorithm.
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm" ti=
tle=3D"Euclidean algorithm">Euclidean algorithm</a> determines the greatest=
 common divisor (gcd) of two integers, say <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" sty=
le=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span>. If <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"=
font-style:italic;">a</span> has a multiplicative inverse modulo <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span>, this gcd must be =
1. The last of several equations produced by the algorithm may be solved fo=
r this gcd. Then, using a method called "back substitution", an expression =
connecting the original parameters and this gcd can be obtained. In other w=
ords, integers <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x<=
/span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">y</spa=
n> can be found to satisfy <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B%C3%A9=
zout%27s_identity" title=3D"B=C3=A9zout's identity">B=C3=A9zout's identity<=
/a>,
</p>
