<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Applications">Applications<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DModular_mult=
iplicative_inverse&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Applications"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket=
">]</span></span></div>
<p>Finding a modular multiplicative inverse has many applications in algori=
thms that rely on the theory of modular arithmetic. For instance, in crypto=
graphy the use of modular arithmetic permits some operations to be carried =
out more quickly and with fewer storage requirements, while other operation=
s become more difficult.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_multiplicative_inverse#cite_note-=
15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> Both of these features can be used to advantage. In particu=
lar, in the RSA algorithm, encrypting and decrypting a message is done usin=
g a pair of numbers that are multiplicative inverses with respect to a care=
fully selected modulus. One of these numbers is made public and can be used=
 in a rapid encryption procedure, while the other, used in the decryption p=
rocedure, is kept hidden. Determining the hidden number from the public num=
ber is considered to be computationally infeasible and this is what makes t=
he system work to ensure privacy.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_multiplicative_inverse#c=
ite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>As another example in a different context, consider the exact divisi=
on problem in computer science where you have a list of odd word-sized numb=
ers each divisible by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i></span> and you wish =
to divide them all by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i></span>. One solution=
 is as follows:
</p>
<ol><li>Use the extended Euclidean algorithm to compute <span class=3D"texh=
tml"><i>k</i><sup>=E2=88=921</sup></span>, the modular multiplicative inver=
se of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>k</i> mod 2<sup><i>w</i></sup></span>, whe=
re <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>w</i></span> is the number of bits in a word.=
 This inverse will exist since the numbers are odd and the modulus has no o=
dd factors.</li>
<li>For each number in the list, multiply it by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
k</i><sup>=E2=88=921</sup></span> and take the least significant word of th=
e result.</li></ol>
<p>On many machines, particularly those without hardware support for divisi=
on, division is a slower operation than multiplication, so this approach ca=
n yield a considerable speedup. The first step is relatively slow but only =
needs to be done once.
</p><p>Modular multiplicative inverses are used to obtain a solution of a s=
ystem of linear congruences that is guaranteed by the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_Remainder_Theorem" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Chinese Remainder Theorem">Chinese Remainder Theorem</a>.=20
</p><p>For example, the system
</p>
<dl><dd><dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">X=
</span> =E2=89=A1 4  (mod 5)</dd>
<dd><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">X</span> =E2=
=89=A1 4  (mod 7)</dd>
<dd><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">X</span> =E2=
=89=A1 6  (mod 11)</dd></dl></dd></dl>
<p>has common solutions since 5,7 and 11 are pairwise <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coprime" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Coprime">coprim=
e</a>. A solution is given by
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">X</span> =
=3D <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>t</i><sub>1</sub></span> (7 =C3=97 11) =C3=
=97 4 + <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>t</i><sub>2</sub></span> (5 =C3=97 11) =
=C3=97 4 + <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>t</i><sub>3</sub></span> (5 =C3=97 7)=
 =C3=97 6</dd></dl>
<p>where
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>t</i><sub>1</sub></span> =3D 3 is the mo=
dular multiplicative inverse of 7 =C3=97 11 (mod 5),</dd>
<dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>t</i><sub>2</sub></span> =3D 6 is the modula=
r multiplicative inverse of 5 =C3=97 11 (mod 7) and</dd>
<dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>t</i><sub>3</sub></span> =3D 6 is the modula=
r multiplicative inverse of 5 =C3=97 7 (mod 11).</dd></dl>
<p>Thus,
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">X</span> =
=3D 3 =C3=97 (7 =C3=97 11) =C3=97 4 + 6 =C3=97 (5 =C3=97 11) =C3=97 4 + 6 =
=C3=97 (5 =C3=97 7) =C3=97 6 =3D 3504</dd></dl>
<p>and in its unique reduced form
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">X</span> =
=E2=89=A1 3504 =E2=89=A1 39 (mod 385)</dd></dl>
<p>since 385 is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Least_common_m=
ultiple" title=3D"Least common multiple">LCM</a> of 5,7 and 11.
</p><p>Also, the modular multiplicative inverse figures prominently in the =
definition of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kloosterman_sum"=
 title=3D"Kloosterman sum">Kloosterman sum</a>.
</p>
